{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}} {{Unreferenced|date=March 2011}} {{Wikisourcelang|fr|Constitution du 22 août 1795|Constitution du 22 août 1795}} The '''Constitution of 22 August 1795''' (also known as the '''Constitution of the Year III''', or the '''Constitution of 5 Fructidor''') was a national constitution of France ratified by the [[National Convention]] on 22 August 1795 (5 Fructidor of the Year III under the [[French Revolutionary Calendar]]) during the [[French Revolution]]. It established the [[French Directory|Directory]], and remained in effect until the [[coup d'etat|coup]] of [[18 Brumaire]] (9 November 1799) effectively ended the Revolution and began the ascendancy of [[Napoleon Bonaparte]]. It was more conservative than the abortive democratic [[French Constitution of 1793]]. The Constitution of 1795 established a liberal republic with a franchise based on the payment of taxes, similar to that of the [[French Constitution of 1791]]; a bicameral legislature, ([[Council of Ancients]], and a [[Council of 500]]) to slow down the legislative process; and a five-man Directory. The central government retained great power, including emergency powers to curb [[freedom of the press]] and freedom of association. It was succeeded by the [[Constitution of the Year VIII]], which established the [[French Consulate|Consulate]].
